 have been used as a nickname, perhaps for someone who played the part of an armed knight in a local pageant.","Irish: sometimes adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac an Ridire</b> ‘son of the knight’. See also   McKnight  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Knights","meanings":["English (East Anglia): variant of   Knight  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"McKnight","meanings":["Irish: part translation of Gaelic <b>Mac an Ridire</b> ‘son of the horseman (Gaelic <i>ridire</i>)’, formerly Anglicized <i>McRuddery</i>.","Scottish (Dumfriesshire and Galloway) and Irish (Ulster): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Neachtain</b>, which is usually Anglicized as   McNaughton  ."]}]},{"name":"Piers","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Regular medieval vernacular form of   Peter   (from the Old French nominative case, as against the oblique <i>Pier</i>, modern <i>Pierre</i>). In the form <i>Pierce</i> it survived into the 18th century, although in part this may be a transferred use of the surname derived from the medieval given name. <i>Piers</i> was revived in the mid-20th century, perhaps partly under the influence of  William Langland's  great rambling medieval poem Piers Plowman (  1367–86 ), in which the character of Piers symbolizes the virtues of hard work, honesty, and fairness."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Piers Knight II was born in 1224, in Ashill, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Piers Knight, of Panworth, was 46 and his mother, Mrs Piers Knight of Panworth, was 45. He married Mrs. Agatha De Nerford. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 15 July 1262, at the age of 38."},"et":{"1224–15 July 1262":"1224–15. juuli 1262","1224–1262":"1224–1262","1225–Female":"1225–Surnud","1249–1302":"1249–1302","1179–1239":"1179–1239","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","1239":"1239","BEF JUN 1239":"enne juunit 1239","1249":"1249","1302":"1302","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","11